<div id="review_1265414126" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1265414126" />
    <a title="Adrian Charles" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3002193-adrian-charles"><img alt="Adrian Charles" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1284158282p2/3002193.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1265414126?book_show_action=true">Apr 27, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Adrian Charles" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Adrian Charles" href="/user/show/3002193-adrian-charles">Adrian Charles</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1265414126" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4798225917283612316">“Sweetness in the Belly”, by Camilla Gibb. ****<br/><br/>A lush, leisurely love story— but the principal love interest is Ethiopia: people, culture, and religion.<br/><br/>The novel tells the story of an Ethiopian Muslim woman of white Irish parentage, and her experience as a teen Ferengi (‘outsider’) in Ethiopia, and a refugee after resettlement in London in 1974.<br/><br/>She leaves her heart in Ethiopia, in more ways than one, and the tale is part coming-of-age story, part romance novel— but mainly an account of Ethiopian</span>
  <span id="freeText4798225917283612316" style="display:none">“Sweetness in the Belly”, by Camilla Gibb. ****<br /><br />A lush, leisurely love story— but the principal love interest is Ethiopia: people, culture, and religion.<br /><br />The novel tells the story of an Ethiopian Muslim woman of white Irish parentage, and her experience as a teen Ferengi (‘outsider’) in Ethiopia, and a refugee after resettlement in London in 1974.<br /><br />She leaves her heart in Ethiopia, in more ways than one, and the tale is part coming-of-age story, part romance novel— but mainly an account of Ethiopian culture, as seen through the eyes of a protagonist who is immersed, but not fully accepted.<br /><br />It is told in slices alternating between Ethiopia’s turmoil leading up to the deposition of Haile Selassie, and the refugee experience in London in the 1980s.<br /><br />Highly recommended.<br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="4798225917283612316" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
