    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1934924947" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1934924947" />
    <a title="Ashleigh Marshall" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/64510883-ashleigh-marshall"><img alt="Ashleigh Marshall" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1934924947?book_show_action=true">Mar 20, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ashleigh Marshall" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ashleigh Marshall" href="/user/show/64510883-ashleigh-marshall">Ashleigh Marshall</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1934924947" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12720515853903006538">&quot;Sweetness in the Belly&quot; is about a young women whose parents were English and Irish hippies who left her orphaned at a very young age due to their death. She then stayed with a family friend in Morocco, a priest who taught her, the Muslim religion. From growing up she did not have friends and all she did was study the Quran. But finally around the age of sixteen she was sent to live on her own and to seek shelter from the religious leader of Harar. But since she was a foreigner and did not look</span>
  <span id="freeText12720515853903006538" style="display:none">"Sweetness in the Belly" is about a young women whose parents were English and Irish hippies who left her orphaned at a very young age due to their death. She then stayed with a family friend in Morocco, a priest who taught her, the Muslim religion. From growing up she did not have friends and all she did was study the Quran. But finally around the age of sixteen she was sent to live on her own and to seek shelter from the religious leader of Harar. But since she was a foreigner and did not look like a traditional Muslim she was sent away, refused. She found shelter in a single mothers household and had to earn her way by teaching the poor children of Harar the Quarn. Everyone hated her but soon after her lessons the people started to accept her. This book is about her journey in Harar and migrating to Europe and becoming this intelligent nurse. This book would be good for someone who wants a mind opener and a chance to explore another culture through time.<br /><br />One thing I like about this book is how serious the text is, it was extremely sophisticated. It was elegant and refined in every way. It opened up my mind to a entirely new and different culture. I never understood how much a religion meant to someone until I read this book. I myself don't have a strong religious connection at all and reading this text made me want to believe in something more.<br /><br />Another thing I liked about this book was how descriptive it was, and how it really identified certain aspects of the culture that you wouldn't find in other books. It was very educational, for example the book had a section that educates the reader on female circumcision and how it is a part of their culture, whereas in America or other parts of Europe it would be frowned upon to even talk about it. But in the Harari culture the entire community of women come to see the task in person.<br /><br />One thing I don't really like about the book is how it has the time hops. It took me forever to finally understand the book because I didn't realize it had moved back or forward in time. When it moved back the culture, environment, and the language totally transitioned and changed the form. But overall I suppose it was well written. <br /><br />So this book like I said was simply elegant, sophisticated, and well written. It was a new writing style and topic for me. It makes me want to read more sophisticated books, ones with a purpose, to educate. I recommend this book to young adults but I think most could not handle or comprehend the theme and meaning of this until an appropriate older age. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12720515853903006538" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

