<div id="review_1846835952" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1846835952" />
    <a title="Sandra The Old Woman in a Van" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/38024473-sandra-the-old-woman-in-a-van"><img alt="Sandra The Old Woman in a Van" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1592505438p2/38024473.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1846835952?book_show_action=true">Jan 18, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sandra The Old Woman in a Van" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sandra The Old Woman in a Van" href="/user/show/38024473-sandra-the-old-woman-in-a-van">Sandra The Old Woman in a Van</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38024473-sandra-the-old-woman-in-a-van?shelf=audiobook">audiobook</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38024473-sandra-the-old-woman-in-a-van?shelf=region-africa">region-africa</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38024473-sandra-the-old-woman-in-a-van?shelf=bipoc">bipoc</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38024473-sandra-the-old-woman-in-a-van?shelf=2020-around-the-year-in-52-books">2020-around-the-year-in-52-books</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1846835952" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11520516171016839720">This book pulled me in so that I listened to it all in one day. The primary character is unique, a young woman with a complex history the leaves her hanging between multiple cultures. This allows her to, on the one hand, be more like an observer of her surrounding - a living narrator. On the other hand, as a the key character, it set up conflict and a struggle to belong that is the stage for the story. <br/><br/>The universal struggle for identity and belonging is a central them of the novel. At the same </span>
  <span id="freeText11520516171016839720" style="display:none">This book pulled me in so that I listened to it all in one day. The primary character is unique, a young woman with a complex history the leaves her hanging between multiple cultures. This allows her to, on the one hand, be more like an observer of her surrounding - a living narrator. On the other hand, as a the key character, it set up conflict and a struggle to belong that is the stage for the story. <br /><br />The universal struggle for identity and belonging is a central them of the novel. At the same time, its setting in Harar Ethiopia brings the reader an opportunity to explore a place and culture not often available in Western literature. <br /><br />I have spent a lot of time traveling in Ethiopia, including a short visit while the Derg was in power. While I have never visited Harar, I recognized Ethiopia. This aspect of the book is done with exceptional clarity. The experience of the Derg refugees is also well done. I have family and friends who are refugees from that era, and I found the portrayal of the people and experiences very familiar.<br /><br /> Some reviewers did not like the book because the portrayal of Islam did not match their view. None, that I read, were Ethiopian or seemed to have much experience with Islam as it is practiced there. I am not Muslim and cannot comment on accuracy of the religious details. I can only say that the book is not a text about Islam, nor is it intended to be. I don’t feel I have much of an impression of the religious details. It is part of the setting because of the protagonists unusual upbringing and because Harar has largely a Muslim population. Not describing Islamic practices would be like writing a book set in Italy and not including Catholicism. <br /><br />If you are looking for a book that transports you to a different time and place, where you can travel and experience the world from your armchair, you will enjoy this book. If you are interested in understanding the refugee and immigrant experience in all its complexity, you will also find this book a complex and thoughtful exploration of the topic. <br /><br />A strong recommendation, also for book clubs. <br /><br />Note - a few Ethiopian words were mispronounced. Not to distraction, but if this bothers you in an audio-book be advised. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="11520516171016839720" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


