<div id="review_58436597" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/58436597" />
    <a title="Noel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/291748-noel"><img alt="Noel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1426796200p2/291748.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/58436597?book_show_action=true">Jun 04, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Noel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Noel" href="/user/show/291748-noel">Noel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/291748-noel?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/291748-noel?shelf=lit-and-fiction">lit-and-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/291748-noel?shelf=culture-clash">culture-clash</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/291748-noel?shelf=ethiopia">ethiopia</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer58436597" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6264983350498929921">Sweetness in the Belly follows the story of Lilly Abal, the daughter of an English father and Irish mother, both world wanderers and hippies. She grows up in Morocco, but is orphaned by age 8 and is brought up by a devout Muslim who teaches her the Qu&apos;ran. When Moroccan internal strife forces her to leave the country, she winds up living in Haran, Ethiopia in a compound of women and children who are all leery of this white farenji, who seems to speak not only English, but Arabic and Amharic. Lil</span>
  <span id="freeText6264983350498929921" style="display:none">Sweetness in the Belly follows the story of Lilly Abal, the daughter of an English father and Irish mother, both world wanderers and hippies. She grows up in Morocco, but is orphaned by age 8 and is brought up by a devout Muslim who teaches her the Qu'ran. When Moroccan internal strife forces her to leave the country, she winds up living in Haran, Ethiopia in a compound of women and children who are all leery of this white farenji, who seems to speak not only English, but Arabic and Amharic. Lilly grows up within the circle of women, in abject poverty, sleeping on the floor, fighting parasites in infected water, drought, and female infibulation. She winds up using her knowledge of Islam to begin teaching the children who cannot afford a madrassa; this wins her some favor with the locals. She has some fairly strict ideas and limits as to what is allowed or not by her religion. She meets Aziz, a doctor, who pushes her limits and stretches her knowledge of not only herself but of her beliefs, but soon after Lilly must flee Ethiopia for political reasons. She winds up living in London and working as a nurse at a refugee center and volunteering at a center to reunite misplaced persons. Once again Lilly must try to come to terms with a new culture, and finds it harder to let go than some of her born and raised Ethiopians. <br /><br />That's the story in a nutshell, however within its many layers, the author explores a form of African Islam, closely tied to their culture, which we don't often see in our newspapers and reports. We see a young lady having to make some decisions about what she has learned and what is entrenched in her very being; of thinking outside the box and making changes. The backdrop of Ethiopia's political strife, of corruption, power and reign of terror is present but does not bog down the book, rather it just explains the historical times. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6264983350498929921" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


