<div id="review_68792022" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/68792022" />
    <a title="Ozma" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1152262-ozma"><img alt="Ozma" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1210401167p2/1152262.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/68792022?book_show_action=true">Aug 25, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ozma" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ozma" href="/user/show/1152262-ozma">Ozma</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1152262-ozma?shelf=one-of-my-favorites">one-of-my-favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1152262-ozma?shelf=book-club-pick">book-club-pick</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer68792022" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11276942697208641443">I really loved this book. I think every Muslim should read it. It captured how I feel about being a Muslim -- that sense of brother/sister-hood with your fellow Muslims of all different races and backgrounds; the misuse of culture. The descriptions of Harar, the ancient, walled, Muslim city of Ethiopia, were beautiful and wonderful. I have actually visited Harar, so it might have meant more to me, but I think anyone reading it gets a sense of the magical grit of Harar. Also, the author captures,</span>
  <span id="freeText11276942697208641443" style="display:none">I really loved this book. I think every Muslim should read it. It captured how I feel about being a Muslim -- that sense of brother/sister-hood with your fellow Muslims of all different races and backgrounds; the misuse of culture. The descriptions of Harar, the ancient, walled, Muslim city of Ethiopia, were beautiful and wonderful. I have actually visited Harar, so it might have meant more to me, but I think anyone reading it gets a sense of the magical grit of Harar. Also, the author captures, in a fictional tone, the misuse of Islam to justify cultural practices and also the misuse of the term JIHAD. The author stops just short of a full-on gush over Islam and Ethiopia, which I totally was ripe to hear, but I can understand how she restrained a bit. I would have also liked some more lush description of the female protagonist's childhood (orphaned after her hippie parents die on the street selling drugs, raised by a Sufi shaykh in his monastery), her romance, how she ended up back in England. . .But, when I recall how stark life is in Ethiopia, the stark style of the novel makes sense: it reflects the landscape. My dermatologist, who was raised by missionary parents in Ethiopia, recommended this book to me. There is one scene NOT for the faint of heart. You know it's coming so just skip over it when you get there.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11276942697208641443" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

