    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_230909189" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/230909189" />
    <a title="Rizwan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6773509-rizwan"><img alt="Rizwan" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/230909189?book_show_action=true">Nov 03, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rizwan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rizwan" href="/user/show/6773509-rizwan">Rizwan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6773509-rizwan?shelf=novels">novels</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6773509-rizwan?shelf=religious-islamic-studies">religious-islamic-studies</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6773509-rizwan?shelf=anthropology">anthropology</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer230909189" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6928616987704242041">While sometimes uneven, an insightful, sensitive and lyrical entree into Ethiopia through the interactions of a British-Muslim convert and her host culture in 1960s and 70s Muslim Harar. Alternating between refugee life in Britain and evocative memories of a life once-lived, a time of stabliity replaced by political change under the waning years of Haile Selassie, the orchestrated deceit of media and the lustre of innnocent socialist promise in the wake of dictatorial reign, the book is as timel</span>
  <span id="freeText6928616987704242041" style="display:none">While sometimes uneven, an insightful, sensitive and lyrical entree into Ethiopia through the interactions of a British-Muslim convert and her host culture in 1960s and 70s Muslim Harar. Alternating between refugee life in Britain and evocative memories of a life once-lived, a time of stabliity replaced by political change under the waning years of Haile Selassie, the orchestrated deceit of media and the lustre of innnocent socialist promise in the wake of dictatorial reign, the book is as timely in our world as it is in the world it attempts to represent.<br /><br />It is also simultaneously a meditation on Islam's conversation with lived experience and an attempt to wrestle with understanding the various tides which claim to represent it - both at the level of the person and with culture. Sweetness in the Belly is at once a story of love, redemption, moving on and anchoring oneself in a new world amidst a memoried past riddled with the phantom bullets of sweeping change upon the landscape of once youthful confidence.<br /><br />Gibb, with the trainined eye of an ethnographer brings the relationships and daily life of the walled city of Harar come alive and provides a rare gendered view into the secrets that continue to be preserved there.<br /><br />A relatively effortless and immersive read into a world now made more accessible.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6928616987704242041" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


